Here's a complete formula sheet for CBSE Class 11 Economics - Correlation in JSON format:

```json
[
  {
    "name": "Pearson's Correlation Coefficient Formula",
    "formula": "r = Σ[(xi - x̄)(yi - ȳ)] / (√Σ(xi - x̄)² * √Σ(yi - ȳ)²)",
    "variables": {
      "r": "Pearson's correlation coefficient",
      "xi": "Value of the independent variable",
      "x̄": "Mean of the independent variable",
      "yi": "Value of the dependent variable",
      "ȳ": "Mean of the dependent variable"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Karl Pearson's Coefficient of Correlation",
    "formula": "r = -1 ≤ r ≤ 1",
    "variables": {
      "r": "Pearson's correlation coefficient"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": "Range of values for Pearson's correlation coefficient"
  },
  {
    "name": "Spearman's Rank Correlation Coefficient Formula",
    "formula": "r = 1 - (6 * Σd²) / (n² - 1)",
    "variables": {
      "r": "Spearman's rank correlation coefficient",
      "d": "Difference in ranks of corresponding pairs",
      "n": "Number of observations"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Kendall's Tau Coefficient Formula",
    "formula": "τ = (Number of concordant pairs - Number of discordant pairs) / (Total number of pairs)",
    "variables": {
      "τ": "Kendall's tau coefficient"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Correlation and Causation",
    "formula": "Correlation does not necessarily imply causation",
    "variables": "",
    "units": "",
    "notes": "Important note to remember when interpreting correlation coefficients"
  }
]
```

Note that all variables and symbols used in the formulas are explained in the "variables" section for each formula.
